<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
        Bluetooth permission prompt copy.

        macOS shows this string verbatim in the Privacy → Bluetooth
        consent dialog when the bundled `pim-daemon` first invokes
        `blueutil --inquiry` to discover nearby PIM peers. Without this
        key the prompt is suppressed and Bluetooth scan returns an
        empty result silently.

        The string must explain WHY the app needs Bluetooth — Apple
        rejects bundles whose copy is generic or evasive.
    -->
    <key>NSBluetoothAlwaysUsageDescription</key>
    <string>pim uses Bluetooth to discover nearby mesh peers and establish PAN links to them. Without this permission you can still connect over Wi-Fi LAN.</string>

    <!-- Legacy key for older macOS releases (pre-13). Apple's docs
         recommend keeping both for compatibility. -->
    <key>NSBluetoothPeripheralUsageDescription</key>
    <string>pim uses Bluetooth to discover nearby mesh peers and establish PAN links to them. Without this permission you can still connect over Wi-Fi LAN.</string>

    <!--
        Local network access prompt copy.

        Required on macOS 15+ (Sequoia) for any process that sends or
        receives multicast/broadcast on the LAN — which the daemon does
        constantly via `[discovery]` UDP broadcasts on :9101.
    -->
    <key>NSLocalNetworkUsageDescription</key>
    <string>pim broadcasts its presence on the local network so other mesh peers can find it without manual configuration.</string>
</dict>
</plist>
